Diagnosis.
Fore wing with costal, subcostal, basal, marginal, and stigmal veins sclerotized; poststigmal, radial, and postmarginal veins visible as weak traces and not forming a closed radial cell, radial vein curved (
Fig. 5B
). Mesopleuron with epicnemial carina developed only antero-ventrally (
Fig. 4E
).

Mesosoma.
Pronotum coarsely rugose between epomia in dorsal view; pronotal shoulders angled; lateral side of pronotum smooth posteriorly from epomia and sculptured along the vertical branch of epomia; mesoscutum smooth and convex; notauli complete, crenulate; humeral sulcus longer than tegula, crenulate; scutellum convex, sculptured along posterior margin (
Fig. 4D
) (other characters of scutellum invisible); metanotum narrow, bare and coarsely rugose, metascutellum with three longitudinal keels, median keel prominent (
Fig. 4B
); propodeum in dorsal view, short, almost bare, coarsely rugose, with two elongate carinae medially (
Fig. 4D
); propleuron sculptured anteriorly, smooth and bare posteriorly; mesopleuron in lateral view with deep mesepimeral sulcus, sculpture antero-dorsally below tegula and with distinct epicnemial carina (
Fig. 4E
); mesopleuron in ventral view with acetabular carina behind fore-coxa and crenulate mesodiscrimen; metapleuron and propodeum coarsely rugose laterall with few short, scattered setae; fore tarsal claws with a row of strong setae ventrally (
Fig. 5A
, red arrows), mid and hind claws simple; fore and mid legs slender; hind tibiae gradually swollen with carina on inner side.

subSection.paragraph:
Hosts of the extant Ismaridae belong to Aphelopinae and Anteoninae . The supposed oldest Aphelopinae from the early Barremian Lebanese amber was transferred to the monotypical subfamily, Archaeodryininae (
Olmi et al. , 2020
). Biological features of
Aphelopus
that enabled parasitism on Typhlocybinae ( Hemiptera : Cicadellidae ) are discussed in the same paper. Typhlocybinae are the most common cicadellids in European ambers (see
Dietrich et al. , 2023
), so the absence of Aphelopinae in European amber (
Olmi et al. , 2020
) is enticing. In the collection of NHMD were found two specimens of Typhlocybinae (Dietrich, in prep.) parasitized by Dryinidae (Olmi, pers. comm., 2023), but the parasitoids belong to Anteoninae (Olmi, pers. comm., 2023) that are unknown as parasitoids of extant Typhlocybinae . Anteoninae are known in fossil resins since the mid-Cretaceous (
Olmi et al. , 2021a
), and the extant genus
Lonchodryinus
is known since the late Eocene (
Olmi et al. , 2021b
). The supposed reason for the rarity of the
Lonchodryinus
in amber forests could be that most of their extant hosts are connected with herbaceous plants (
Olmi et al. , 2021b
). Still, finding two specimens of Typhlocybinae parasitized by Anteoninae in NHMD indicates that Anteoninae could be not so rare in the European amber forests. One of these Typhlocybinae is from Danish amber (
Simutnik et al. , 2023
), making it the third dryinid species ( Perkovsky and Olmi, 2018 ) and third dryinid specimen (our data) reported from Danish amber. The paratype specimen of
Lubomirus victori
from NHMD could belong to the big (selected by Jens-Wilhelm Janzen) collection of diaprioids obtained by Karin Nordmann ( Buhl, 2002 ) and later purchased by NHMD ( Brazidec and Vilhelmsen 2022 ), but Baltic amber collection PIN 964 is unbiased collection as well as the Rovno amber collection of SIZK ( Dlussky and Rasnitsyn, 2009 ;
Perkovsky et al. , 2012
), and Ismaridae constitute 1.4% of non-ant hymenopterans in this collection (Rasnitsyn, pers. comm. 2023), so ismarids must be not so rare in European amber forests. Interestingly, the single reported dryinid from collection PIN 964 is anteonine
Deinodryinus areolatus ( Ponomarenko, 1975 ) ( Ponomarenko, 1975 )
. Thus, one of the reasons of anteonines rarity in the fossil resins could be the selectivity of the amber trap; in the actualistic paleontological studies (
Zherikhin et al. 2009
) only one dryinid specimen was reported (less than 0.5% of all solitary hymenopterans), and this specimen does not belong to the anteonines that are relatively common and diverse in the studied areas.All in all, reported Eocene ismarids could be proxies for Anteoninae and indicate the unknown Eocene diversity of the subfamily.
Lubomirus masneri
sp. nov.
described from the Rovno amber may indirectly indicate the presence of Anteoninae in the Rovno amber fauna. It is especially interesting that the Rovno ismarid specimen must be from Klesov, and even Dryininae are still unknown from this deposit (
Martynova et al. 2019
). It seems unlikely that Bocchinae could be the host of the new genus for two reasons. Firstly, the only known Bocchine parasitoid belongs to Encyrtidae (Olmi, pers. com. 2024). Secondly, Bocchinae species were extremely rare in the Baltic amber forest, with only a single specimen known in this well-studied and abundant fauna (
Perkovsky et al. 2020a
;
Olmi et al. 2022
). So, the uncommon abundance and diversity of Bocchinae (
Perkovsky et al. 2020a
;
Olmi et al. 2022
) could be not the single peculiarity of the Rovno amber dryinid fauna.
